{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b9cb9423-7d13-4042-abdd-54b1d2bf4e8f","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports the modern approach. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    // TestContext is injected automatically via init-property (MSTest 3.x+)\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; init; }\n\n    // Synchronous initialization — runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public void Setup()\n    {\n        // sync setup logic\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous initialization — runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // async setup logic (e.g., database seeding, HTTP calls)\n        await Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`TestContext`** — use `{ get; init; }` (not the legacy `static` property from class-level `[ClassInitialize]`). MSTest 3.x injects it automatically.\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — can return `void` (sync) or `Task` (async). You can have both on separate methods; they'll both run before each test.\n- For **one-time** class-level setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (static) and `[ClassCleanup]` similarly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5cedd555-6275-4a8c-a25d-09b774527b81","outputTokens":347},"id":"afecf464-5b6a-4773-9f5d-52248294a666","timestamp":"2026-04-03T03:26:41.855Z","parentId":"db0eba37-e66f-488b-9acf-1b2333572c2d"}
